## üéØ Clinical Applications

### Primary Pattern & Manifestations
**Pattern**: Yangming bowel heat with qi stagnation (milder than Da Cheng Qi Tang)
**Key Symptoms**: Constipation, abdominal distension, mild abdominal pain, dry mouth, slight thirst, restlessness
**Tongue**: Yellow coating (less thick than Da Cheng Qi Tang)
**Pulse**: Rapid and forceful (less than Da Cheng Qi Tang)

### Secondary Applications
- Mild to moderate heat constipation
- Post-operative constipation
- Elderly constipation with qi stagnation
- Constipation with abdominal bloating
- Early stage intestinal obstruction
- Preparation for bowel procedures

### Modern Clinical Uses
- Functional constipation
- Post-operative ileus
- Irritable bowel syndrome with constipation
- Bowel preparation for procedures
- Mild intestinal obstruction
- Chronic constipation in elderly

## üìù Therapeutic Actions
**Primary**: Purge heat, move qi, relieve constipation

**Secondary**: Reduce bloating, clear intestinal heat, promote normal bowel function

## üîÑ Modifications & Variations

### Common Additions
| Condition | Add Herbs | Rationale |
|-----------|-----------|-----------|
| Severe heat signs | Mang Xiao | Stronger heat-clearing and purging |
| Qi deficiency | Ren Shen + Gan Cao | Support qi while purging |
| Blood stasis | Tao Ren + Hong Hua | Move blood and qi together |
| Dryness | Huo Ma Ren + Yu Li Ren | Moisten intestines |

### Classical Variations
- **Da Cheng Qi Tang**: Add Mang Xiao for stronger purging action
- **Tiao Wei Cheng Qi Tang**: Remove Hou Po for milder action
- **Hou Po San Wu Tang**: Focus on qi stagnation aspect

### Modern Modifications
- For post-operative ileus: Add Chen Pi and Sha Ren
- For elderly: Reduce Da Huang, add moistening herbs
- For IBS-C: Add Bai Shao and Gan Cao

